'''Carrot and stick''' is a term ([[idiom]]) used to refer to the act of simultaneously rewarding good behaviour while punishing bad behaviour. For example, if a worker is slacking off using a [[company]] provided [[privilege]] or [[asset]], the company may give the worker something similar (usually allowance of use or a certain discount) at home while restricting his/her access to the privilege at work. Effectiveness generally varies per worker.

An older interpretation is the use of a carrot dangling on a stick in front of an uncooperative mule, so that the encouragement is constant, but the satisfaction is permanently elusive.  The "and" implies the use of both, while the phrase "carrot '''or''' stick" would imply the reward/punishment interpretation.

== History ==
Before the invention of the [[automobile]], if one wanted a [[horse]] to pull a [[cart]], but the horse was refusing, one had some choices: The subject could dangle a [[carrot]] in front of him (which he probably would like) in the hopes that he walks towards it, or one could hit him with a [[stick]], which he would not like and would want to move away from.

The phrase usually applies now to motivating people, not horses. Controversy has ensued for years about which methods are more effective.

